@encode/maintainers If someone is against this idea, or has any concerns regarding this, or want more context, anything... Please let us know. Otherwise, I'll get this merged end of next week.

Okay. Thanks for the discussion. Here are my comments.

Since this machinery was developed with constraints/plans different from
our current ones, my goal is to reduce the _conceptual surface area_ of
this interface as much as possible, but not further. (For instance, by
removing the layout system in #4240.)

## Group names

Currently, elements are keyed by both render group name and cache key.
Render group names are intended to accommodate having one renderer with
multiple “drawables”: e.g., a scalar chart that with a `SeriesLineView`
but also an `InteriorTickView` and `ErrorBarView`. But: (a) we have no
current plans to introduce such patterns, and (b) this only punts the
problem to figuring out unique names for the render groups. (I’m not
convinced that using `this.constructor.name` for the group is a great
solution. Not only is it [unhygienic][hy], it also means that you can
only have one of each class of drawable per renderer, so I don’t think
that it really solves the problem.)

Since we don’t intend to expose this API publicly, if we do decide that
we need it later, we can add it then.

[hy]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hygienic_macro 

Thus, I propose removing group names, at which point “`renderGroup`”
just becomes (per your suggestion) “`updateScene`”:

```typescript
interface Renderer {
  // Invoke a callback that calls `drawLine` to populate all objects
  // currently in the scene. Then, update the rendered view to match the
  // described state. Callback must not call `updateScene`, `onResize`.
  updateScene(renderBlock: () => void): void;

  // Draw a line. Must only be called inside `updateScene`. If called
  // multiple times for the same `cacheId` inside one `updateScene`
  // block, the last call wins.
  drawLine(cacheId: string, polyline: Polyline, paintOpt: LinePaintOption);

  // Repaint current scene state in response to viewport change.
  onResize(domRect: Rect): void;

  // ???
  flush();
}
```

## Remove `flush`

I don’t see why this needs to be part of the public API. It might make
sense as an abstract method on `BaseCachedObjectRenderer` to be called
at the end of `renderGroup`, but clients should never call it directly,
right?

## Scope drawing methods

You’re only allowed to call `drawLine` from within a render group. Make
the invalid states unrepresentable:

```typescript
interface Paintbrush {  // TODO(@stephanwlee): name?
  // Draw a line. If called multiple times for the same `cacheId`, the
  // last call wins.
  drawLine(cacheId, polyline, paintOpt);
}

interface Renderer {
  // Invoke a callback that calls `drawLine` to populate all objects
  // currently in the scene. Then, update the rendered view to match the
  // described state. Callback must not call any method on this instance.
  updateScene(renderBlock: (Paintbrush) => void);

  // Repaint current scene state in response to viewport change.
  onResize(Rect);
}
```

## _Consider_ making scene elements data, not calls

There is a sense in which these are equivalent:

```typescript
// Imperative API
renderer.updateScene((p) => {
  p.drawLine("foo", fooPts, fooOpts);
  p.drawLine("bar", barPts, barOpts);
  p.drawEllipse("baz", bazPts, bazOpts);
});

// Declarative API
const scene = new Map();
scene.set("foo", {type: "LINE", points: fooPts, opts: fooOpts});
scene.set("bar", {type: "LINE", points: barPts, opts: barOpts});
scene.set("baz", {type: "ELLIPSE", points: bazPts, opts: bazOpts});
renderer.updateScene(scene);
```

The declarative approach has some benefits:

  - While constructing the scene, you can `scene.delete` to “un-paint”
    an element. Once you’ve called `drawLine`, you can’t do that.
  - The “last element wins” semantics are obvious from the semantics of
    `Map`. Sure, the last `drawLine` call for an ID wins, but what if
    I call `drawLine("foo", ...); drawEllipse("foo", ...)`? Does it
    override the shape type, or is this illegal, or are they separate?
  - No need for callbacks, eliminating issues like “the callback passed
    to `updateScene` must not itself call `updateScene`”
  - With this API, it is actually somewhat easy to re-implement render
    group scoping compositionally by implementing this signature:

    ```typescript
    scopedRenderers(delegate: Renderer): (groupName: string) => Renderer;
    ```

    (You can do it the other way, too, but you basically end up needing
    to transform it into the declarative form.)

Over chat you seemed less than enthusiastic about this idea, so I’m
proposing it here merely as an idea.

---

Thoughts? I think this is the extent of my large interface-level
suggestions, so after these are implemented probably just one more round
of review should suffice.

The implementation looks right to me

Not necessarily the end of the world, but "InputManager" in the name PySparkCsvInputManager feels a little weird to me, given that it's actually a full IO manager.

A case to consider is when the upstream asset doesn't have any IO manager at all, i.e. when it has a `Nothing` output. E.g.
```
@op(out=Out(Nothing, name="users"))
def my_op():
    create_db_connection().execute("create table users as ...")

@op(ins={"users": In(input_manager_key=...)}
def downstream_op(users: DataFrame):
    ...
```

In that case, there wouldn't be an upstream IO manager to extend. The most straightforward way to define an input manager might look something like the way you define an root_input_manager (no need to make a class, just decorate a function).

Looks great to me! Two questions about the cleanup gRPC cleanup routine. 

I'd recommend trying to manually validate (probably don't need to add a full test) one additional error case. The failure mode for gRPC requests and the provider chain is a little more complicated to reason about. A program like this will fail without the GCP project and zone set. Might be work running the equivalent in python just to make sure the error is caught and the automation script terminates gracefully (no hangs);

```ts
const run = async () => {
    // This is our pulumi program in "inline function" form
    const pulumiProgram = async () => {
        // this call fails if gcp:project and gcp:zone are not set. 
        const engineVersion = gcp.container.getEngineVersions().then((v) => v.latestMasterVersion);
        return {
            engv: engineVersion
        };
    };

    // Create our stack 
    const args: InlineProgramArgs = {
        stackName: "dev1",
        projectName: "inlineNode",
        program: pulumiProgram
    };

    // create (or select if one already exists) a stack that uses our inline program
    const stack = await LocalWorkspace.createOrSelectStack(args);

    console.info("updating stack...");
    try {
        const upRes = await stack.up({ onOutput: console.info });
        console.log(`update summary: \n${JSON.stringify(upRes.summary.resourceChanges, null, 4)}`);
    }
    catch (e){
        console.log(e)
        process.exit(1)
    }
};

run().catch(err => {
    console.log("there was an error")
    console.log(err)
    console.log("error logged")
});
```

@franferrax, great, thanks for your contribution.

Do I see it right, that while this works, it doesn't seem to be [documented](https://jira.atlassian.com/secure/WikiRendererHelpAction.jspa?section=links) (or anywhere else) by Atlassian?

Next, do you think you could also add a unit test to cover this new feature? I think cloning and extending the existing `test_render_link()` as `test_render_link_with_title()` could be sufficient. :)

